      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"workouts\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":62,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":371,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Start at the comfortable end of your easy range — 6:11/km or even a touch slower for the first few minutes. Let your body wake up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":52,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Settle into a comfortable aerobic pace between 5:24 and 6:11/km. This is a true easy day — conversational effort throughout. Your aerobic system is building its foundation here.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Bring pace back down to the slow end of easy. Finish feeling like you could have run another 30 minutes.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"No structured warmup needed beyond easing into the first 5 minutes at a very comfortable pace.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Easy walk for 2–3 minutes after you stop. Light calf and Achilles stretching given your history — gentle, not aggressive.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Monday's easy run sets the tone for the week. With a maintenance goal, the purpose here is to keep your aerobic base humming without accumulating fatigue. Think of this as active recovery from the weekend's long run. You're running at a pace where a full conversation is genuinely comfortable — not just possible. At your fitness level, the temptation is always to drift faster. Resist it. The physiological adaptation here happens in the easy zone.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"workout_type\":\"Tempo\",\"title\":\"Lactate Threshold Cruise Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":12,\"target_duration_minutes\":65,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":269,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":15,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"15 minutes at easy pace (5:45–6:11/km). Include 4–5 strides of 20 seconds at threshold effort in the final 3 minutes to prime the system.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First cruise interval at threshold pace — 4:29/km. This should feel comfortably hard: you can speak a few words but not a full sentence. Steady and controlled.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2-minute easy jog recovery. Use this to lower your heart rate slightly before the next effort.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second cruise interval at 4:29/km. Match the effort of the first — aim for even splits.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":2,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"2-minute easy jog recovery.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":269,\"intensity\":\"Threshold\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third cruise interval. If the first two felt controlled, hold the pace. If not, effort over pace — back off 5 seconds/km rather than straining.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":12,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"12 minutes of easy running back toward your easy range. Let your breathing fully recover before you stop.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Full 15-minute warmup is important before threshold work. Don't shortchange this — cold threshold running increases injury risk and the quality of the intervals suffers.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"At least 10–12 minutes of easy running after the last interval. Follow with gentle Achilles and calf mobilization.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Cruise intervals at threshold pace are the cornerstone of maintaining your lactate threshold — the pace you can sustain for roughly an hour of racing. Three 8-minute efforts with short recoveries keeps the stimulus meaningful without the fatigue of a continuous tempo run. At 4:29/km, this should feel like controlled discomfort — not a race effort. The 2-minute jog recoveries are intentionally short: you're training your body to clear lactate efficiently, not fully recovering between efforts. Total threshold work is 24 minutes, which is appropriate for a maintenance week.\",\"perceived_effort\":7},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Recovery Run\",\"target_distance_km\":9,\"target_duration_minutes\":56,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":385,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":385,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":56,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"This is a genuine recovery run — stay at the slower end of your easy range (5:50–6:11/km) the entire time. Your legs should feel a little heavy after yesterday's threshold work. That's normal. Don't chase pace.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start walking for 2 minutes before you begin. No need for a formal warmup beyond that — this whole run is the warmup.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"2-minute walk to finish. This is a good day for a longer, gentler Achilles stretch routine if your tendon feels any tightness.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The day after a quality session, easy truly means easy. This run flushes metabolic byproducts, promotes blood flow for repair, and keeps your aerobic volume up without adding meaningful stress. The temptation after a good Tuesday session is to feel great and run faster — hold back. The adaptation from Tuesday happens during this recovery window. Slightly shorter and slower than Monday is intentional.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"workout_type\":\"Interval\",\"title\":\"VO2max Intervals\",\"target_distance_km\":13,\"target_duration_minutes\":70,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":248,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"20 minutes easy, finishing with 3–4 light strides (20 seconds each at roughly interval effort) in the final 5 minutes. This primes your neuromuscular system for the work ahead.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":248,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 5-minute interval at 4:08/km. This is hard — around 9/10 effort. You should not be able to speak in sentences. Controlled aggression.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"4-minute easy jog recovery. Full recovery before the next effort — VO2max intervals require near-complete recovery to maintain quality.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":248,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Second 5-minute interval. Match effort, not necessarily pace — if the legs are heavy, 4:10–4:12/km is fine.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"4-minute easy jog.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":248,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Third interval. By now, effort will feel harder for the same pace. That's the point. Stay controlled and don't sprint the last 30 seconds.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Recovery\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"4-minute easy jog.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":248,\"intensity\":\"VO2Max\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Fourth and final interval. If you've paced well, this one should feel like your hardest. Finish strong but not desperate.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":13,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"At least 12–15 minutes of easy running. Your body needs this transition time — stopping abruptly after hard intervals is not ideal for recovery.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"The 20-minute warmup is non-negotiable for interval work. Your cardiovascular system and muscles need adequate preparation before 4:08/km efforts. Strides in the warmup significantly improve the quality of your first interval.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"12–15 minutes easy jogging, then walk 3 minutes. Gentle dynamic stretching for calves and Achilles. Hydrate and refuel within 30 minutes.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"VO2max intervals are the most physiologically potent stimulus in your training toolkit. Four 5-minute efforts at 4:08/km challenge your maximal oxygen uptake and improve your running economy. For a maintenance phase, this is appropriate volume — enough to preserve your aerobic ceiling without the cumulative fatigue of a build phase. The 1:1 work-to-recovery ratio (5 on, 4 off) allows enough recovery to genuinely hit interval pace on each rep. If you can only complete 3 quality efforts, that's a successful session — quality over quantity every time.\",\"perceived_effort\":9},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"workout_type\":\"Recovery\",\"title\":\"Easy Recovery Run or Rest\",\"target_distance_km\":8,\"target_duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":385,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":385,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":50,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Very easy running — stay at 6:00–6:11/km or slower. If your legs feel genuinely beat up from Thursday's intervals, this is a great day to swap for a 30-minute cross-training session (cycling, swimming) or full rest. Listen to your body.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Walk 3–5 minutes before starting. This run is light enough that a formal warmup isn't needed.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Short walk to finish. A good day for foam rolling calves and glutes if you have time.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Friday sits between two quality sessions — Thursday's intervals and Sunday's long run. Its job is purely recovery. The pace should genuinely feel embarrassingly slow if you're used to running faster. That's correct. The physiological goal here is circulation, not stimulus. If you feel any unusual fatigue, tightness, or strain — especially around the Achilles — this is the day to rest rather than run. Your training history and injury history both support erring on the side of caution on Fridays.\",\"perceived_effort\":3},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"title\":\"Easy Aerobic Run with Strides\",\"target_distance_km\":10,\"target_duration_minutes\":62,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":231,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"5 minutes at the easy end of your range to warm up.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":45,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Comfortable easy running at 5:24–6:00/km. This is a relatively fresh day heading into the long run — save your energy. Keep effort genuinely easy.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":8,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":231,\"intensity\":\"Repetition\",\"repetitions\":4,\"notes\":\"4 x 20-second strides at near-repetition pace (roughly 3:51/km effort). Run tall, relaxed, fast — not a sprint. Walk or jog 60–90 seconds between each. These keep your neuromuscular system sharp without adding fatigue.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":4,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"4 minutes easy to close. Finish feeling fresh and ready for tomorrow's long run.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Light and easy. You're preserving freshness for Sunday — don't overcook Saturday.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 2 minutes. Light stretching. Hydrate well this evening in preparation for the long run tomorrow.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"Saturday's run is deliberately easy to protect Sunday's long run quality. The four strides at the end serve a specific purpose: they maintain neuromuscular sharpness and running economy without meaningful aerobic cost. Think of strides as maintenance for your fast-twitch fibers — you're reminding your legs they can move quickly, which translates to efficiency at all paces. Keep the main body of this run genuinely conversational. Tomorrow is the centerpiece of the week.\",\"perceived_effort\":4},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"title\":\"Aerobic Long Run\",\"target_distance_km\":20,\"target_duration_minutes\":120,\"target_pace_easy_sec_per_km\":371,\"target_pace_fast_sec_per_km\":371,\"segments\":[{\"segment_type\":\"Warmup\",\"duration_minutes\":10,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"First 10 minutes at 6:00–6:11/km. Ease into the run — your body needs time to settle into long run rhythm.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":85,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":371,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"The bulk of your long run at easy pace — 5:24–6:00/km. This is entirely aerobic: fat oxidation, capillary development, connective tissue strengthening. Keep the effort genuinely comfortable. If you're going uphill, slow down rather than maintain pace.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Work\",\"duration_minutes\":20,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":287,\"intensity\":\"Moderate\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Optional: if you feel good in the final 20 minutes, you might gradually drift toward marathon pace (4:47/km) — but only if it feels natural, not forced. This is not a requirement. Easy running for the full duration is equally valid.\"},{\"segment_type\":\"Cooldown\",\"duration_minutes\":5,\"target_pace_sec_per_km\":385,\"intensity\":\"Easy\",\"repetitions\":1,\"notes\":\"Final 5 minutes — bring the pace back down to easy or walk the last few minutes home.\"}],\"warmup_notes\":\"Start conservatively. Long runs that start too fast lead to the last 5km being a grind. Your pace should feel almost too easy in the first 15 minutes.\",\"cooldown_notes\":\"Walk 5 minutes after finishing. Stretch calves, Achilles, hip flexors gently. Refuel and rehydrate within 30–45 minutes — a combination of carbohydrates and protein. Prioritize sleep tonight.\",\"coaching_notes\":\"The long run is the cornerstone of every distance runner's week, and at 20km it's a well-calibrated length for your current maintenance phase. The physiological benefits are substantial: enhanced fat oxidation, increased mitochondrial density, improved connective tissue resilience, and greater glycogen storage capacity. All of this at easy pace. There's no performance goal here — this is infrastructure work. Given your Achilles history, the cap at 120 minutes is appropriate. Your long run is already at a strong maintenance length, so there's no need to push beyond 20km this week. If the optional marathon-pace finish feels good in the final 20 minutes, it's a lovely way to close the run — but it's genuinely optional, not a metric to hit. Hydration and fueling during the run (every 30–45 minutes) will support quality in the back half.\",\"perceived_effort\":6}]}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
  "modelId": "\"claude-sonnet-4-6\"",
  "finishReason": "stop",
